<HEAD>Brazilian Elections Bad News for Ecologists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SILVERSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sweeping victories by
conservatives in last week's congressional and gubernatorial races
will mean bad news for the rain forest and its defenders,
environmentalists say.
   Conservatives won a large majority in last week's voting, and
showed special strength in the nine states of the Amazon region.
   ``Almost all . . . are totally opposed to ecological concerns
and rational development,'' Fernando Gabeira, a leader of Brazil's
small Green Party, said over the weekend.
   The federal government sets most environmental policy, but
political scientist David Fleischer of the University of Brasilia
noted: ``Almost all policy enforcement is carried out by local
authorities. If they show no interest in protecting the
environment, decisions at the federal level lose much of their
impact.''
   Right-wing candidates for governor won outright victories in
three of the nine states and were headed for Nov. 25 runoffs in the
other six.
   Only in two small states, Acre and Amapa, did pro-ecology
candidates even get to the runoffs.
   Candidates had to win an absolute majority to take a first-round
victory.
   In congressional races, conservatives won at least 11 of the 13
senate chairs at stake in the Amazon region and all but a few of
the house seats.
   Rightist populists have long dominated the impoverished region.
Much of their success comes from support by major landowners, who
traditionally control the votes of the rural poor.
   Many voters also view environmentalism as an attempt to block
economic growth and lock the Amazon into perennial backwardness.
   Slash-and-burn techniques used by ranchers and farmers have
already destroyed about 8 percent of the 2-million-square-mile
wilderness, according to government figures.
   In Amazonas, the area's largest state, incoming governor
Gilberto Mestrinho favors widescale destruction of the rain forest
to promote large mining and agricultural projects.
   The state's new senator, Amazonino Mendes, proposed handing out
chain saws to settlers to speed the felling of the forest.
   In neighboring Roraima state, both gubernatorial finalists
openly opposed federal plans to remove thousands of gold miners
from the territory of the Yanomami Indians, the world's largest
remaining primitive tribe.
   The miners illegally search for gold, diamonds and other
minerals on Indian land. Armed clashes and imported diseases killed
about 1,500 of the tribe's remaining 9,000 members in the past
three years.
   The favorite in Roraima's gubernatorial race is Romero Juca, now
on trial for illegally authorizing logging on Indian land when he
was chief of the National Indian Foundation in the early 1980s.
   ``The elections in Roraima could spell the end for the
Yanomami,'' Fleischer remarked,
   In Para state, the runoff pits anti-ecology candidates Jaber
Barbalho and Sahid Xerfan.
   Para has been the site of repeated clashes between Indians and
miners. Miners have dumped about 600 tons of mercury from gold
prospecting into the Tapajos River.
   ``We have no preference in Para,'' Gabeira said. ``Neither
possible winner will defend the Indians or the Amazon.''
   Big farmers are blamed for most of the violence plaguing the
region. More than 1,000 peasant activists were killed in land
conflicts in the past decade.
   The Rev. Ricardo Resende of the Pastoral Land Commission said in
a phone interview from Para state, ``The new governors are well
known and most have never demonstrated any interest in protecting
the region's poor. Small farmers will continue to be expelled from
their land.''
   His commission is linked with the Roman Catholic Church.
   Gabeira said the only bright spot was in Acre, home to thousands
of rubber tappers, where Jorge Viana of the pro-environmentalist
Workers Party won a spot in the second round.
   His strength is largely attributed to the legacy of
world-renowned unionist and ecologist Chico Mendes, a Workers Party
activist murdered in 1988. Mendes' alleged killers are going on
trial Oct. 25, and the publicity could boost Viana's campaign.
   There was another note of encouragement to the rain forest's
advocates Sunday contained in an article in the newspaper Jornal do
Brasil.
   It reported that the area of the Amazon rain forest destroyed by
fires in 1990 was down considerably from last year. Data compiled
by Brazil's National Institute of Space Research showed overall
destruction may be down by as much as 50 percent, the newspaper
said.
   Institute President Marcio Barbosa was quoted as saying that the
space satellite that monitors the Amazon has been crucial to
efforts to prevent further damage.
</TEXT>
