<HEAD>Rubber Tapper Says Plotters of Chico Mendes Killing Still at Large
^By PETER MUELLO
^Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A successor to slain Amazon
environmentalist Chico Mendes says the men who planned that killing
continue to threaten witnesses and rubber tappers.
   Osmarino Amancio Rodrigues, 33, said Tuesday that rubber tappers
believe a group of businessmen and ranchers masterminded the Mendes
shooting but were never called to testify in the case.
   ``The head of the snake was not hit,'' Rodrigues told a group of
foreign journalists. ``Those who planned it are still at large.''
   Mendes, a rubber tapper who led a movement to stop destruction
of the rain forest, was shot to death on Dec. 22, 1988, at his home
in the western Amazon town of Xapuri.
   A cattle rancher and his sons were arrested for the shooting.
They have not yet been brought to trial.
   Rodrigues said four rubber tappers have been shot to death in
the region since Mendes was slain. One victim, Jose Brito, had been
slated to testify in the trial.
   ``He was going to testify how Chico Mendes' death was planned,''
Rodrigues said. ``But two guys on a motorcycle shot him down right
on the street.''
   Those who oppose the ranchers get frequent anonymous death
threats, he said: ``They call up and say, `Is Chico Mendes OK?
How'd you like to be ``OK'' like Chico?'''
   A prime target is Rodrigues himself, he said. As president of
the rubber tappers union in Brasileia, near Xapuri, he has emerged
as a leader of conservationist movement, carrying on Mendes'
struggle to save the Amazon jungle from destruction.
   Rodrigues is constantly accompanied by four union bodyguards
plus a police escort but said he still doesn't feel safe.
   He sharply criticized the Amazon policy of President Fernando
Collor de Mello, who took office in March.
   Collor got high marks from conservationists for nominating
renowned ecologist Jose Lutzenberger as Environment Secretary and
ordering the expulsion of gold miners from Indian reservations.
   But Rodrigues said there have been few practical results.
   Rodrigues said the government must learn that the rain forest
can be profitably developed without destroying it. Slash-and-burn
clearing by ranchers and farmers has destroyed an estimated 8
percent of the 2 million-square-mile Amazon wilderness.
   Rubber, Brazil nuts, cocoa and tropical fruits are abundant in
the Amazon but often rot for lack of processing or transportation,
he said.
   Rodrigues has toured Europe and the United States to raise money
for the conservation movement. Despite many pledges of funds, not a
cent has reached Brazil yet, he said.
   Foreign aid will help environmentalists stand up to ranchers,
mining interests and loggers who buy the votes of the poor and
control local politics, Rodrigues said.
</TEXT>
