<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
<HEAD>PORTO VELHO, Brazil: of visibility.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Marcos da Costa Pereira, a physicist with the space institute,
says, ``The burning of the Amazon is not only poisoning the
atmosphere and affecting the earth's ozone layer, it is also
reducing the rain forest's capacity to produce oxygen.''
   He says that although it is an exaggeration to call the Amazon
the ``lungs of the world,'' a phrase often found in press accounts,
the Brazilian jungle is a ``major contributor of the oxygen
breathed by mankind.''
   Along BR364, the 900-mile asphalt highway that slices through
the jungle to connect Porto Velho to Cuiaba, capital of the state
of Mato Grosso, the charred and still smoldering remains of once
majestic Brazil nut, rubber and brazilwood trees stand in mute
testimony to man's destructiveness.
   Along the highway, homesteaders, their faces blackened by trees
turned to charcoal, struggle to clear their land and plant crops
such as rice, corn and cassava before the rains come.
   Raimundo Nonato de Souza, 50, owns 123 acres of land about 60
miles outside Porto Velho. He burned about 50 acres to plant
cassava, a tropical root that yields a coarse flour and serves as
``bread'' for impoverished peasants.
   During a break from work, he wipes perspiration from his brow
with his forearm and says, ``This is the second time I have burned
this plot. Next year, nothing will grow on it, and I will have to
burn some more of my land.''
   Neither Souza, his 38-year-old wife, Raimunda, nor their two
young children have any idea what the greenhouse effect is all
about. But, expressing a kind of instinctive concern, the Brazilian
says, ``I know it's wrong to burn the jungle, but I have no other
choice. I have no money to buy a tractor, which would let me clear
the land without burning it.''
   Souza, like thousands of other homesteaders, received his plot
free of charge from the government. ``But before I could receive
title to my land, I was told I had to clear it off, and the best,
cheapest and fastest way to do so was to slash and burn.''
   Another peasant farmer, Oscar Fernandes, 48, asks, ``Where am I
supposed to grow the food to feed my family? On top of the trees?
If I don't cut down the forest and burn it, I will starve.''
   Catanhede, of the Brazilian Forest Service, says the worst
offenders are the owners of large cattle ranches who ``burn more
and more land each year to create pastureland to feed their growing
herds.
   ``After two or three burnings the land is completely depleted of
all its nutrients. Nothing will grow on it. The farmer then slashes
and burns some more virgin forest to continue growing crops, and
the cattle raiser does the same to get more pastureland.''
   The Forest Service tries to control the burnings by issuing
special licenses and setting limits on how much can be burned on a
given property.
   Penalties for burning without a license are fines equivalent to
$725 dollars per acre affected and prison sentences of up to one
year.
   But the law is widely flouted. Debt-ridden Brazil doesn't have
enough forest rangers or policemen to make the rules stick, and,
besides, most of the jungle burners couldn't afford the fines
anyway.
   ``What we would really like is to be able to enforce the law
that says a property owner must reforest the area he has
destroyed,'' Catanhede says. ``But with only 15 forest guards to
keep an eye over more than 90,000 rural properties in the entire
state and with no funds to increase our manpower, controlling the
burnings becomes an impossible task.''
   Francisco de Assis Araujo, head of Rondonia's Environmental
Protection Agency, says his office has been trying to educate
farmers to plant perennial crops such as coffee, cacao, and rubber,
mango and orange trees.
   ``The land would have to be slashed and burned only once to grow
such crops and thus repeated burnings and further destruction would
be avoided,'' he says.
   But homesteaders like Souza and Fernandes, who have little or no
education and who emigrated from other parts of Brazil where their
lives were even more wretched than in Rondonia, say they never
received any instructions or guidance from the government.
   Araujo says the Rondonia state government was about to implement
an ``agro-ecological zoning plan'' to specify which areas were
ecologically suitable for different agricultural activities and
cattle raising, thereby protecting, theoretically, the jungle from
unnecessary destruction.
   But he says Brazil's federal government, facing political
opposition because of a record 800 percent annual inflation rate,
views efforts to educate farmers about the proper use of the soil
as ``superfluous expenditures which just increase the public
deficit.''
</TEXT>
