<HEAD>Fewer Fires in Amazon This Year But Damage Still Extensive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of fires set in the
Amazon rain forest has dropped from last year but the region is
still suffering extensive damage, government scientists said
Wednesday.
   They say the burning increases the amount of carbon dioxide in
the atmosphere and adds to the greenhouse effect, which causes a
global warming.
   Marcos Pereira, a researcher at the Space Studies Institute, said
experts in the past two months detected 59,000 fires that devastated
12,700 square miles of forest _ an area larger than Maryland.
   That represents roughly 1.5 percent of the so-called legal
Amazon, a 2 million-square-mile region.
   ``We're certainly going to have fewer fires and less destruction
in 1989 than in 1988, primarily because we've had unusually heavy
rains this year,'' Pereira told The Associated Press by telephone
from Sao Jose dos Campos, 210 miles southwest of Rio.
   In 1988, about 45,600 square miles were destroyed by 205,000
fires, Pereira said.
   The institute monitors fires in the Amazon by using satellites
that detect smoke and heat.
   Pereira said the government helped reduce the number of fires,
mainly by suspending incentives for large-scale agricultural and
ranching projects.
   It also began a plan this month to monitor part of the region by
helicopter and fine those found guilty of clearing the forest
illegally.
   Officials handed out $9 million in fines in the first 15 days.
   ``There's a greater awareness of the problem, on the part of the
government and individuals, and that will make it easier to protect
the Amazon,'' Pereira said.
   Ranchers and farmers burn off large tracts of the rain forest to
clear land for planting and grazing.
</TEXT>
